king encoder/decoder settings. MappedEncoding should create via an implicit definition if MappedEncoding and Encoder[String] are in the scope. But local ambiguity could create problems. I’m also contemplating the need for nested companion object names, which seem to generate warnings. Maybe I should create a simple final case class for Email to avoid these issues. It feels like I might need a more robust approach and think about skipping problematic encodings to ensure the user’s request is fulfilled.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering encoder options**\\n\\nI'm concerned that if the next run fails due to mapped encoding issues, that wouldn't be good. I might consider proactively switching to a custom encoder/decoder rather than using MappedEncoding. The downside is that then I wouldn't be testing mapped encodings at all, which seems like a missed opportunity. Dynamic coverage includes encoders, especially for common scalars, but it could really enhance the process with user-defined encoding too. It's a tricky balance!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_zpAhpxVk76IjE0kQsGwSVqbz|fc_016979b3c33f99ac0169faabb45e44819eab755d3d1e312ceb", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/io.getquill/quill-jdbc_2.13/4.8.5/src/test/scala/io_getquill/quill_jdbc_2_13/Quill_jdbc_2_13Test.scala", "edits": [{"oldText": "import java.sql.SQLFeatureNotSupportedException\n", "newText": "import java.sql.SQLFeatureNotSupportedException\nimport java.sql.Types\n"}, {"oldText": "  def mappedEncodingsAreAppliedForUserDefinedValueTypes(): Unit = {\n    implicit val encodeEmail: MappedEncoding[Email, String] = MappedEncoding[Email, String](_.value)\n    implicit val decodeEmail: MappedEncoding[String, Email] = MappedEncoding[String, Email](Email.apply _)\n", "newText": "  def customEncodersAndDecodersAreAppliedForUserDefinedValueTypes(): Unit = {\n    implicit val encodeEmail: Encoder[Email] = encoder(Types.VARCHAR, (index, value, row) => row.setString(index, value.